    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm working on an embedded c++ project for an automotive control unit and we're seeing a slow memory leak. the system runs fine for a few hours but then eventually runs out of available ram and crashes. i don't see any obvious missing deletes in my main loop. how should i go about systematically finding where the leak is happening?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A memory leak in an embedded system, especially one running for hours, is a classic case of a resource being held onto longer than necessary. You'll need a system-level approach, like tracking the allocation and deallocation of memory, which is often tricky in bare-metal environments. Consider using a custom memory allocator wrapper or a heap monitoring tool if your RTOS supports it, which can track every `malloc` and `free` call. If that's too complex, try instrumenting your code by adding counters before and after every heap operation to see which functions are responsible for the most allocations without corresponding frees. This methodical approach should help you pinpoint the leaky section.",
      "source": "target",
