      "role": "user",
      "content": "the state machine thing makes sense, i'll re-check the transition logic. but it just feels so elusive, like it's intentionally avoiding my debugger or hiding in some tiny corner of the code i haven't thought of. is there a way to automate finding these \"hidden\" leaks without having to manually audit every single state transition myself?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Automating the hunt for these hidden leaks in a complex state machine is challenging, but you can employ a technique called **\"snapshotting\"** or **\"heap differencing.\"** This involves taking a snapshot of the memory usage (or the list of allocated blocks) at the start of a known operational cycle, and then taking another snapshot after the cycle completes. If the memory usage has increased between snapshots without a corresponding functional reason, you've found a leak tied to that cycle.\n\nIf you are using a custom heap manager, you can modify it to maintain a list of all currently allocated pointers. At key points in your state machine (like entering a major state or completing a major task), you log the size and count of these active allocations. By comparing these logs, you can isolate which state transition is responsible for the persistent growth. This is far less manual than auditing every line of code.",
      "source": "target",
